      "item": {
        "id": "f1e84abd-9eb3-4943-80b7-7b84c72e00e1",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "De Forest also used the arc-transmitter to conduct some of the earliest experimental entertainment radio broadcasts ([[birth of public radio broadcasting]]). Eugenia Farrar sang \"I Love You Truly\" in an unpublicized test from his laboratory in 1907, and in 1908, on de Forest's Paris honeymoon, musical selections were broadcast from the Eiffel Tower as a part of demonstrations of the arc-transmitter. In early 1909, in what may have been the first public speech by radio, de Forest's mother-in-law, Harriot Stanton Blatch ([[Harriot Eaton Stanton Blatch]]), made a broadcast supporting women's suffrage."
      },
      "date": 1514554873661
